<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Graduate Who Mentors Troubled Teens Wins James Madison Fellowship</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Kristi Bartlett
		
		<span class="date">May 10, 2006</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE570/en_US/balmacrop.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Courtesy of Jason Balma</p>
			
			<p></p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=00240041068876a7f010acd497c480077f3">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:jbiema303@yahoo.com ">Jason Balma</a></h4>
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.jamesmadison.com">James Madison Memorial Fellowship Foundation</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>University of Central Florida graduate Jason Balma, a social science education major who established a mentoring program for troubled teenagers, has won a Junior Fellowship from The James Madison Memorial Fellowship Foundation.</p><p>About 50 Junior Fellowships are awarded nationwide to students who plan to study American history and politics and the Constitution in graduate school. Balma, who graduated last week, plans to remain at UCF to pursue a masters degree in social science education with a concentration in political science.</p><p>Each winner receives $24,000 to pay for graduate school tuition, books and room and board. Fellows also attend the four-week Summer Institute at <city /><place />Georgetown</place /></city /> after their first year of graduate school. </p><p>Balma, of <city /><place />Fort Myers</place /></city />, was recognized for his leadership on campus and his community service. </p><p>As the leader of UCFs wrestling club team, Balma established a juvenile delinquent mentoring program. The team visits the Orange County Jail to discuss values such as dedication, leadership and the importance of education with 15- to 17-year-olds. Many of them are without peer role models and benefit from one-on-one sessions with successful student-athletes. The program has been in place for five years. </p><p>I became involved in the program as a way to provide teens with motivation, hope for success and deterrence from future criminal activity, Balma said. </p><p>William Gaudelli, Balmas mentor and a professor in the <place /><placetype />College</placetype /> of <placename />Education</placename /></place />, suggested that he apply for the fellowship. </p><p>Jason displays a sharp critical capacity and stood out in the classroom, Gaudelli said He is dedicated and interested in his field. </p><p>Balma pursued a career in education because his interactions with coaches and teachers showed him that one motivated person can influence a life. He chose social science education and constitutional studies because he believes that the Constitution should be the backbone of all teaching. </p><p>It is important to prepare students for a democratic life, and constitutional themes should be the focus throughout ones teachings, he said. </p><p>Balma plans on staying in <place />Central Florida</place /> after completing his masters degree to fulfill the fellowships teaching obligation. He wants to teach in a high school. </p><p>Balma has received the Whos Who: 100 Best and Brightest at UCF Award for Leadership and the 2006 National Intramural-Recreational Sports Associations William N. Wasson Student Leadership and Academic Award. </p><p>The Madison Fellowship was established by Congress in 1986 to improve the teaching of the Constitution in secondary schools. It is funded through Congress and contributions from individuals, corporations and foundations. The fellowships were created to honor the legacy and principles of James Madison and his role in the creation of the Constitution. </p><p>Balma is the second UCF student to receive a junior fellowship during the past two years. Stacey Repass was awarded one last year. </p><p>For more information on the fellowships, go to <a href="http://www.jamesmadison.com/">www.jamesmadison.com</a>. The full list of 2006 winners will be posted later on that site. </p>
		
	
